"the book of painting. On these considerations I have shunned hemistichs ; not being willing to imi- tate Virgil to a fault, like Alexander’s courtiers, who affected to hold their necks awry, because he could not help it. T am confident your lordship is by this time of my opinion, and that you will lock on those half-lines hereafter, as the imperfect pro- ducts of a hasty Muse—like the frogs and serpents in the Nile: part of them kindled into life, and part a lump of unformed unanimated mud,"